          <h2 style="font-size: 24px; line-height: 1.2; font-weight: 500">Trump’s U-turn on Ukraine</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px 0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>Summary: Trump sends Patriot missiles to Ukraine and threatens 100% tariffs on Russia.</strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The what:</strong> President Trump confirmed that the US will supply Patriot missiles to Ukraine through NATO and warned that a <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-15-jul-25-spotlight-h2-5-100-tariff-on-russian-goods?source=website" target="_blank">100% tariff on Russian goods</a> will take effect if peace isn’t reached in 50 days. The White House also announced secondary tariffs on countries that continue buying Russian oil. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          <strong>The why:</strong> After several failed peace attempts, Trump is showing a tougher stance. By sending missiles through NATO, he is showing determination to back Ukraine, while avoiding direct US expenses and criticism. Each Patriot missile is valued at approximately $1B.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          Four different agendas are shaping this conflict: 
          </p>
        </mj-text>
