              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Religious conservatism in Malaysia</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>Summary: A growing push for strict Islamic policies in Malaysia is putting unity at risk in this ethnically diverse country.</strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
           <strong>The what:</strong> Malaysia is seeing a shift towards a more <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-15-jul-25-analysis-h1-6-conservative-islamic-policy?source=website" target="_blank">conservative Islamic policy</a>. The Islamic party is pushing for hudud (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-15-jul-25-analysis-h1-7-islamic-criminal-law?source=website" target="_blank">Islamic criminal law</a>), stricter dress codes, and gender segregation in public spaces. This rise, often called the “green wave,” has put Malaysia’s liberal democracy in jeopardy. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The why:</strong> The rise of political Islam comes from public dissatisfaction with the government. Many Malays feel let down by the corruption (particularly the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-15-jul-25-analysis-h1-8-1mdb-scandal?source=website" target="_blank">1MDB scandal</a>), restricted job options, and poor education under the current leaders. They are using discontent to promote stricter Islamic policies as solutions to national problems.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
           <strong>The challenges:</strong> Malaysia’s leaders face a difficult task of responding to conservative Mulsim demands while protecting the rights of minorities, who account for 35% of the population. The “<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-15-jul-25-analysis-h1-9-green-wave?source=website" target="_blank">green wave</a>” provides a possibility for dialogue, but balancing faith and diversity remains a major challenge.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
